The change to use `Private` all the time instead of `NonPublicAccessibilityMOdifier` is technically a change in behavior in the following situation (simplification of `completionEntryForClassMembers2.ts`):

```ts
class C {
    protected m(): void {}
}
interface I extends C {}
class D implements I {
    /**/
}
```

Previously we would not provide a completion for `m`, now we will. But I don't think this matters because the situation is impossible to implement -- you can't override `m` because it's private, but you have to implement it to implement the interface, so it's just illegal to implement `C` without extending from it anyway.

